<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-224-237 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 406 554</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Feb 11 1991 v8 n6 p53(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Infrared transceiver links portable PCs to hard-wired LANs.andO;(Photonics Corp.'s PhotoLink wireless networking transceiverconnects microcomputers to local area networks) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sullivan, Kristina B.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Photonics Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Photonics Infrared Transceiver (Computer communications equipment)(Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionTransceivers (Computer Networks)Local Area NetworksWireless Networks.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Kristina B. SullivanandM;Photonics Corp. recently announced a new infrared wireless networkingtransceiver designed for use with portable computers.andM;The Infrared Transceiver, a smaller version of Photonics' PhotoLink desktopproduct, allows users to link their portable computers into existinghard-wired networks, gaining full access to networking resources, accordingto Gary Hughes, CEO of Photonics, based in Campbell, Calif.andM;Like PhotoLink, the Infrared Transceiver supports networking protocols suchas AppleTalk that operate under 1M bps.andP;  Future versions of the product willwork with 10M-bps Ethernet and 4M-bps Token-Ring networks, according toHughes.andM;Portable computers equipped with the transceiver will also be able to connectto machines located within 30 square feet of each other, according to Hughes.andO;For example, he said, &quot;if a number of portable computer users were in aclassroom, they could work on a project together.&quot;andM;The Infrared Transceiver, which is available immediately, is priced at $20 inOEM quantities.andM;Photonics Corp. can be reached at (408) 370-3033.andO;</TEXT></DOC>